page.title: 01SW Keying Marsh/Humber Bank
page.content: This area is predominantly arable farmland of exceptionally high quality, very flat, with no woodland and little area of trees and hedges. Most of this area is alluvial silt land reclaimed over the last 300 years. A new bank was erected during 1984 to prevent flooding. to the south of this bank lies an area of brackish salt marshleading to extensive mudflats which can be half a mile wide at low tide. This whole arrea is abundant in wildfowl. A small part of the river Humber falls within this block. There are very few buildings in the area just four farms and a few attendant houses.
